[7] owner's discussion of end–product sales was not unfair or prejudicial;

[8] award of post–verdict supplemental damages was warranted;

[9] enhancement of damages award by factor of 1.75 was warranted; and

[10] civil contempt sanction of $500,000 was warranted as against one manufacturer.

Affirmed.

"]

["s: The Court of Appeals, O'Malley, Circuit Judge, held that:

[1] Board's decision to exclude public corporation's annual reports was not abuse of discretion;

[2] test preparation company's use of mark was not likely to cause confusion;

[3] opposer failed to establish that its “COACH” mark for fashion accessories was famous for dilution purposes;

[4] opposer had standing to challenge company's use of mark;

[5] substantial evidence supported Board's decision that company's use of mark was merely descriptive; and

[6] remand was warranted so Board could assess whether term had acquired secondary meaning.

Affirmed in part, vacated in part, and remanded.

"]

["s: The Court of Appeals, Newman, Circuit Judge, held that:

[1] complaint had sufficient facial plausibility to allow court to draw reasonable inference that competitor was liable for
patent infringement;

[2]  corporate  officer  did  not  induce  corporation  to  infringe  design  patent,  or  aid  and  abet  corporation's  alleged
infringement;

[3] manufacturer pleaded plausible false advertising claim;

[4] manufacturer sufficiently pleaded possible injury to his business, as required for claim of unfair competition;

[5] manufacturer sufficiently pleaded misappropriation;

[6] principles of patent law preemption do not override potential causes of action based on unfair commercial practices;
and

[7] plausible false advertising issue did not arise from manufacturer's statement that his tote towel was “protected by
my patent.”

 © 2018 Thomson Reuters. No claim to original U.S. Government Works.

1

\x0cHall v. Bed Bath & Beyond, Inc., 705 F.3d 1357 (2013)
2013-1 Trade Cases P 78,244, 105 U.S.P.Q.2d 1672

Affirmed in part, reversed in part, and remanded.

Lourie, Circuit Judge, filed opinion dissenting in part.

"]

['s: The Court of Appeals, Prost, Chief Judge, held that:

[1] “user of said phone” meant a consumer operating the IP phone, rather than a person or thing that uses an IP phone;

[2] district court lacked authority to make correction to add claim limitation;

[3] district court properly refused to consider certificate of correction in determining whether claim was indefinite;

[4] patentee could not assert uncorrected claim; and

[5] apparatus claim describing tangible computer readable medium was invalid as indefinite.

Affirmed as modified.

']

['s: The Court of Appeals held that:

[1] manufacturer failed to establish inequitable conduct by clear and convincing evidence;

[2] patent satisfied written description requirement;

[3] claims relating to ratios of buffers, dosage range, and blood serum concentration levels were invalid for obviousness;

[4] claims directed to non-enteric coated conventional oral dosage forms were not invalid for obviousness;

[5] claims directed to powder formulations were invalid for obviousness;

[6] claims directed to amounts of buffering agent were not invalid for obviousness; and

[7] objective evidence was insufficient to overcome obviousness.

Affirmed in part, reversed in part, and remanded.

Newman, Circuit Judge, concurred in part, dissented in part, and filed opinion

